                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.001 C 76/24: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-01-21T18:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 21, 1921—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 22—2 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>71. I have obtained information that the British Government has not yet been
                    asked by the Greek Government to recognize Constantine. Such request would be
                    refused at present owing to the attitude <pb facs="0242" n="146" xml:id="pg_146"
                    /> both of the French Government and of the British public. The British
                    Government is aware, however, that eventually they must recognize Constantine if
                    they are to accomplish their policy of strengthening Greece. They may be
                    compelled, indeed, to accept revision of the Sevres Treaty in order to maintain
                    cooperation with France and Italy. But for the sake of Greece they will strongly
                    oppose revision, which is one of the principal questions to come before the
                    conference about to meet in Paris. It is expected that very soon thereafter the
                    British Government will be asked and will consent to recognize Constantine.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
